<br>
On the other hand, I'm very concerned about the viewpoint and in some cases ignorance being put forth by a number of people here.  Though I think the US was a bit mean-spirited in this case, they did nothing outside of what was legal.  However, the idea that we shouldn't care for or respect international law is careless.  The idea that we're more important than the rest of the world is tragic.  Of course, given that's been the viewpoint, to greater or lesser degrees of pretty much every administration since Wilson, I'm hardly surprised.  Further the idea that the US goes into other nations 'for their own good' is ludicrous.  Yeah,  Columbia sure needed us to stabalize their government and form a splinter republic so we could build a canal on the cheap.  Hawai'i certainly needed us to stabalize by supporting the ousting of the stable, legitimate government by sugar plantation owners concerned about their bottom line.  Our stabalizations in Vietnam and Iran certainly went wonderfully.  Cuba was certainly in a downright state of revolt when the Bay of Pigs happened.  Good thing for the Cubans we intervened.  Our current support of Columbia's regime is doing wonders for the stability in that region... doing little more than allowing the government to maintain a stalemate against a succesful revolutionary campaign.  The people always benefit from a perpetual state of war, right?  And who could forget Granada?  Heaven forbid we had not invaded Granada and stopped that powderkeg from plunging the entire East Carribean into war.  And though Afghanis are likely benefitting from our intervention and removal of the Taliban, we didn't go there for the sake of stabalization.<br>
<br>
My point here is that everything the US does isn't for the good of the people of the region we're leading an intervention into and stabalizing is often contrary to our goals in the region.  Our actions aren't always bad, nor are our goals always wrong, but keep in mind we aren't often doing things for any goals but our own.  That's okay, just don't take it as something else.<br>
<br>
